ce:section.ce:para:
The development and design of fluorescent probes with simple procedure and low toxicity become critical for the sensing purpose. However, molecular probes often suffer from the complex procedure, while long reaction time is required for nanomaterial-based probes. Here we prepared Si-QDs with trisodium citrate dehydrate and DAMO as the precursors under microwave condition within 15 min (Scheme 1
                        ). The transmission electron microscope (TEM) image of the as-prepared Si-QDs was illustrated in Fig. 1
                        A. Good monodispersity was clearly observed for spherical and uniform particles with the interplanar spacing of 0.22 nm (Fig. 1B), derived from the crystallinity (220) facet of silicon element, indicating the successful formation of Si-QDs. Moreover, the average diameter of Si-QDs was calculated as 3.00 ± 0.01 nm with 220 particles (Fig. 1C). Additionally, a typical XRD analysis confirmed that the Si-QDs were in the amorphous phase (Fig. S1). Fourier transform infrared (FTIR) spectrum confirmed the surface functional groups on Si-QDs (Fig. 1D). The characteristic absorption peaks were observed at 1032 cm−1 and 2931 cm−1 as the stretching vibration of Si-O and C–H bonds [34,44], respectively. The strong absorption peak at 1556 cm−1 was assigned to the bending vibration of N–H bond [45]. The results of FTIR spectrum also demonstrated the successful preparation of Si-QDs.
